{"title_page": "Greg Zanis", "text_new": "{{short description|American carpenter and activist}}\n{{Notability|Biographies|date=May 2020}}\n'''Greg Zanis''' (1950{{snd}}May 4, 2020) was an American carpenter who is most well known for building and delivering personalized [[Christian cross|crosses]] (and some [[Stars of David]] and [[Star and crescent|crescents]]) to shooting victims across the United States.<ref name=\"National Herald 8-8-19\">{{cite news |title=Greg Zanis Places Crosses for Latest Shooting Victims |url=http://www.thenationalherald.com/archive_whats_new/arthro/greg_zanis_places_crosses_for_latest_shooting_victims-22378/ |accessdate=April 27, 2020 |work=The National Herald |date=August 8, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"CBS Vigliotti\">{{cite news |last1=Vigliotti |first1=Jonathan |title=Carpenter travels the country delivering crosses to mass shooting sites |url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/greg-zanis-carpenter-travels-the-country-delivering-crosses-to-mass-shooting-sites/ |accessdate=April 27, 2020 |work=CBS News |date=August 5, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"CNN McLaughlin 4-27-2020\">{{cite news |last1=McLaughlin |first1=Eliott C. |title=Illinois man who spent retirement delivering handmade crosses to mass shootings has weeks to live |url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/04/27/us/greg-zanis-cross-man-cancer/index.html |accessdate=April 27, 2020 |work=CNN |date=April 27, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nZanis was born in Spokane, Washington, and grew up in Nashville, Tennessee. His father was a [[Greek Orthodox]] priest, and his mother, a Greek immigrant, was a seamstress. The family spoke Greek at home.<ref name=\"National Herald 8-8-19\"></ref>\n\n==Crosses for Losses==\nThe first cross that Zanis built was for his own father-in-law, a murder victim.<ref name=\"National Herald 8-8-19\"></ref> Shortly after the 1999 [[Columbine High School massacre]], Zanis constructed 15 crosses (including two for the shooters, [[Eric Harris and Dylan Klebold]]) and delivered them to a park near the site of the shooting. The two crosses for Harris and Klebold were soon cut down by the father of one of the shooting victims.<ref name=after>{{cite web | title=Columbine Shooting Aftermath \u2013 1999 | url=http://www.acolumbinesite.com/after/1999.html | publisher=acolumbinesite.com | accessdate=April 27, 2020 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160828184438/http://acolumbinesite.com/after/1999.html | archive-date=August 28, 2016 | url-status=live | df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nSince that time, Zanis built and delivered over 26,000 crosses, with some [[Stars of David]] and some [[Star and crescent|crescents]] to sites of mass shootings and natural disasters across the United States including the 1 October shooting in Las Vegas (Harvest fest), Parkland, Tree of Life and many others. He founded an organization to raise funds for this effort, called Crosses for Losses. During that time, he kept handwritten notebooks of the names of the victims for whom he built memorials.<ref name=\"CNN McLaughlin 8 2019\">{{cite news |last1=McLaughlin |first1=Eliott C. |title=For 23 years, he\u2019s delivered crosses after massacres. This was his hardest week yet |url=https://www.cnn.com/interactive/2019/08/us/memorial-crosses-dayton-cnnphotos/index.html |accessdate=April 27, 2020 |work=CNN}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nIn late 2019, Zanis was diagnosed with [[bladder cancer]]. He made arrangements to transfer the activities of his organization to the Lutheran Church Charities ministry of the [[Lutheran Church\u2013Missouri Synod]].<ref name=\"CNN McLaughlin 4-27-2020\"></ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{official|https://www.lutheranchurchcharities.org/crossesforlosses.html}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Zanis, Greg}}\n[[Category:1950 births]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Seattle]]\n[[Category:American carpenters]]\n[[Category:People from Aurora, Illinois]]\n[[Category:Mass shootings in the United States]]\n[[Category:Christians from Illinois]]\n[[Category:American people of Greek descent]]\n[[Category:Gun politics in the United States]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American carpenter and activist}}\n{{Notability|Biographies|date=May 2020}}\n'''Greg Zanis''' (1950{{snd}}May 4, 2020) was an American carpenter who is most well known for building and delivering personalized [[Christian cross|crosses]] (and some [[Stars of David]] and [[Star and crescent|crescents]]) to shooting victims across the United States.<ref name=\"National Herald 8-8-19\">{{cite news |title=Greg Zanis Places Crosses for Latest Shooting Victims |url=http://www.thenationalherald.com/archive_whats_new/arthro/greg_zanis_places_crosses_for_latest_shooting_victims-22378/ |accessdate=April 27, 2020 |work=The National Herald |date=August 8, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"CBS Vigliotti\">{{cite news |last1=Vigliotti |first1=Jonathan |title=Carpenter travels the country delivering crosses to mass shooting sites |url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/greg-zanis-carpenter-travels-the-country-delivering-crosses-to-mass-shooting-sites/ |accessdate=April 27, 2020 |work=CBS News |date=August 5, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"CNN McLaughlin 4-27-2020\">{{cite news |last1=McLaughlin |first1=Eliott C. |title=Illinois man who spent retirement delivering handmade crosses to mass shootings has weeks to live |url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/04/27/us/greg-zanis-cross-man-cancer/index.html |accessdate=April 27, 2020 |work=CNN |date=April 27, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nZanis was born in Spokane, Washington, and grew up in Nashville, Tennessee. His father was a [[Greek Orthodox]] priest, and his mother, a Greek immigrant, was a seamstress. The family spoke Greek at home.<ref name=\"National Herald 8-8-19\"></ref>\n\n==Crosses for Losses==\nThe first cross that Zanis built was for his own father-in-law, a murder victim.<ref name=\"National Herald 8-8-19\"></ref> Shortly after the 1999 [[Columbine High School massacre]], Zanis constructed 15 crosses (including two for the shooters, [[Eric Harris and Dylan Klebold]]) and delivered them to a park near the site of the shooting. The two crosses for Harris and Klebold were soon cut down by the father of one of the shooting victims.<ref name=after>{{cite web | title=Columbine Shooting Aftermath \u2013 1999 | url=http://www.acolumbinesite.com/after/1999.html | publisher=acolumbinesite.com | accessdate=April 27, 2020 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160828184438/http://acolumbinesite.com/after/1999.html | archive-date=August 28, 2016 | url-status=live | df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nSince that time, Zanis built and delivered over 26,000 crosses, with some [[Stars of David]] and some [[Star and crescent|crescents]] to sites of mass shootings and natural disasters across the United States including the 1 October shooting in Las Vegas (Harvest fest), Parkland, Tree of Life and many others . He founded an organization to raise funds for this effort, called Crosses for Losses. During that time, he kept handwritten notebooks of the names of the victims for whom he built memorials.<ref name=\"CNN McLaughlin 8 2019\">{{cite news |last1=McLaughlin |first1=Eliott C. |title=For 23 years, he\u2019s delivered crosses after massacres. This was his hardest week yet |url=https://www.cnn.com/interactive/2019/08/us/memorial-crosses-dayton-cnnphotos/index.html |accessdate=April 27, 2020 |work=CNN}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nIn late 2019, Zanis was diagnosed with [[bladder cancer]]. He made arrangements to transfer the activities of his organization to the Lutheran Church Charities ministry of the [[Lutheran Church\u2013Missouri Synod]].<ref name=\"CNN McLaughlin 4-27-2020\"></ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{official|https://www.lutheranchurchcharities.org/crossesforlosses.html}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Zanis, Greg}}\n[[Category:1950 births]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Seattle]]\n[[Category:American carpenters]]\n[[Category:People from Aurora, I